<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1071,153,180]" box="[151,1071,153,180]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,1071,153,180]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,1071,153,180]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
Key to the Colombian species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lepeletier, 1841" authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[559,1071,153,180]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Schonnherria">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[559,671,153,180]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Xylocopa</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[688,856,153,180]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Schonnherria</emphasis>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeletier, A. L. M." box="[873,1071,153,179]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" refId="ref32004" refString="Lepeletier, A. L. M. (1841) Histoire Naturelle des Insectes. Vol. 2. Hymenopteres. Librairie Encyclopedique de Roret, Paris, 680 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 9005" type="book" year="1841">Lepeletier, 1841</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" box="[151,244,225,251]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Females</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="336" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" box="[151,1436,258,280]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,258,280]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
1. Labrum with a distinct, large, single capitate tubercle approximately as large as median ocellus (
<figureCitation box="[1150,1208,258,280]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[167,1423,321,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,309,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Examples of structural characters that are useful for species identification. Comparison of vertex punctation (Figs. 1 and 2). Comparison of the color of hairs on hind basitarsus (Figs. 3 and 4). Comparison of pubescence on T3–T5 (Figs. 5 and 6). Comparison of labrum shape (Figs. 7 and 8). Comparison of upper interocular distance (Figs. 9 and 10)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887578/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
)................. 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
- Labrum with three tubercles with similar size or longitudinally elongated median tubercle and two small sublateral tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[233,290,317,339]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[167,1423,321,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,309,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Examples of structural characters that are useful for species identification. Comparison of vertex punctation (Figs. 1 and 2). Comparison of the color of hairs on hind basitarsus (Figs. 3 and 4). Comparison of pubescence on T3–T5 (Figs. 5 and 6). Comparison of labrum shape (Figs. 7 and 8). Comparison of upper interocular distance (Figs. 9 and 10)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887578/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
)............................................................................................. 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
2(1). Clypeus, paraocular area, gena and lateral sides of T3 and T4 with whitish hairs (
<figureCitation box="[1005,1064,346,368]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[167,1423,321,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,309,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Examples of structural characters that are useful for species identification. Comparison of vertex punctation (Figs. 1 and 2). Comparison of the color of hairs on hind basitarsus (Figs. 3 and 4). Comparison of pubescence on T3–T5 (Figs. 5 and 6). Comparison of labrum shape (Figs. 7 and 8). Comparison of upper interocular distance (Figs. 9 and 10)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887578/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); T2 and T3 with short hairs (0.2–0.4x OD); distinct bluish or greenish highlights on metasoma...................................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
- Pubescence ferruginous or black (
<figureCitation box="[555,614,405,427]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[167,1423,321,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,309,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Examples of structural characters that are useful for species identification. Comparison of vertex punctation (Figs. 1 and 2). Comparison of the color of hairs on hind basitarsus (Figs. 3 and 4). Comparison of pubescence on T3–T5 (Figs. 5 and 6). Comparison of labrum shape (Figs. 7 and 8). Comparison of upper interocular distance (Figs. 9 and 10)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887578/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); T2 and T3 with short hairs barely noticeable (0.1x OD), nearly glabrous; weak (almost absent) bluish and greenish highlights on metasoma..................................................... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
3(2). Black hairs on T1 and T2 and yellowish hairs on T3–T6 and S4–S6; metasomal terga dark brown to black; head, legs and mesoscutum with bluish metallic highlights, greenish on mesoscutellum and metasoma (
<figureCitation box="[1046,1161,493,515]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–42" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1944,1969]" captionTargetBox="[159,1422,645,1912]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1435,633,1919]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 39–42. Female of Xylocopa (Schonnherria) metallica Smith, 1874. Fig. 39. Frontal view. Fig. 40. Detail of metasomal terga. Fig. 41. Dorsal habitus. Fig. 42. Lateral habitus. Scale bar 4 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887594" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887594/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Figs. 39–42</figureCitation>
)................................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith, 1874" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1874" box="[1120,1436,522,544]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1120,1436,522,544]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1120,1309,522,544]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Xylocopa metallica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, F." box="[1315,1436,522,544]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" pagination="247 - 302" refId="ref34236" refString="Smith, F. (1874) Monograph of the genus Xylocopa Latr. Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London, 22, 247 - 302. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1874. tb 00168. x" type="journal article" year="1874">Smith, 1874</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
- Black hairs on metasomal disc with few whitish hairs on T4; metasomal terga black with distinct reddish brown-gold area distally, denser on T2 and T3; integument with bluish highlights on all tagmata (
<figureCitation box="[996,1110,581,603]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1908,1933]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,607,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,597,1883]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 11–14. Female of Xylocopa (Schonnherria) auriventris n. sp. (holotype) Fig. 11. Frontal view. Fig. 12. Detail of metasomal terga. Fig. 13. Dorsal habitus. Fig. 14. Lateral habitus. Scale bar 4 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887580" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887580/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Figs. 11–14</figureCitation>
).... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1170,1437,580,602]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<taxonomicName authority="Villamizar &amp; Fernández &amp; Vivallo, 2020" authorityName="Villamizar &amp; Fernández &amp; Vivallo" authorityYear="2020" box="[1170,1376,580,602]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriventris" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1170,1376,580,602]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Xylocopa auriventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1382,1437,581,602]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
4(2) Metasoma dark brown to black with reddish brown areas on T1–T4; slightly bluish highlights on mesoscutum, tegula and mesoscutellum, without metallic reflections on head, legs and metasoma; pubescence predominantly ferruginous to black; wings dark brown with blue and violet iridescence (
<figureCitation box="[660,775,668,691]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–62" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1944,1969]" captionTargetBox="[159,1422,641,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1435,633,1919]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 59–62. Female of Xylocopa (Schonnherria) simillima Smith, 1854. Fig. 59. Frontal view. Fig. 60. Detail of metasomal terga. Fig. 61. Dorsal habitus. Fig. 62. Lateral habitus. Scale bar 4 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887606" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887606/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Figs. 59–62</figureCitation>
)............................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith, 1854" authorityName=": Smith" authorityYear="1854" box="[1119,1436,668,690]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simillima">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1119,1436,668,690]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1119,1309,668,690]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Xylocopa simillima</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, F." box="[1315,1436,668,690]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" pagination="199 - 465" refId="ref34185" refString="Smith, F. (1854) Apidae. In: Catalogue of hymenopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Part II. British Museum, London, pp. 199 - 465. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 8766" type="book chapter" year="1854">Smith, 1854</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
- Metasoma entirely black; bluish to violet highlights on head and legs and weak greenish on mesoscutellum and metasoma; pubescence predominantly black; wings dark brown with green iridescence apically and violet basally (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1333,727,749]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1493,1518]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,189,1457]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1435,181,1467]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Female of Xylocopa (Schonnherria) dimidiata Latreille, 1809. Fig. 15. Frontal view. Fig. 16. Detail of metasomal terga. Fig. 17. Dorsal habitus. Fig. 18. Lateral habitus. Scale bar 4 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887582" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887582/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Figs. 15–18</figureCitation>
).............................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Latreille, 1809" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1809" box="[1091,1436,756,778]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dimidiata">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1091,1436,756,778]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1091,1282,756,778]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Xylocopa dimidiata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Latreille, P. A." box="[1289,1436,756,778]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" pagination="9 - 138" refId="ref31905" refString="Latreille, P. A. (1809) Insectes de l'Amerique equinoxiale, recueillis pendant le voyage de MM. De Humboldt et Bonpland et decrits par M. Latreille. In: Humboldt, A. &amp; Bonpland, A. (Eds.), Recueil d'observations de zoologie et d'anatomie comparee, faites dans l'Ocean Atlantique, dans l'interieur du nouveau continent et dans le mer du Sud pendant les annees 1799, 1800, 1801, 1802 et 1803. Vol. 2. Schoell, 95, pp. 9 - 138." type="journal article" year="1809">Latreille, 1809</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
5(1). Dorsal surface of mid and hind basitarsus with whitish or yellowish hairs (
<figureCitation box="[957,1016,786,808]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[167,1423,321,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,309,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Examples of structural characters that are useful for species identification. Comparison of vertex punctation (Figs. 1 and 2). Comparison of the color of hairs on hind basitarsus (Figs. 3 and 4). Comparison of pubescence on T3–T5 (Figs. 5 and 6). Comparison of labrum shape (Figs. 7 and 8). Comparison of upper interocular distance (Figs. 9 and 10)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887578/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); whitish or yellowish hairs on disc and/or restricted to laterodistal margins of T2–T4................................................................. 6
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" box="[151,1436,845,867]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,845,867]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
- Mid and hind basitarsus with black hairs (
<figureCitation box="[628,687,845,867]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[167,1423,321,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,309,1888]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Examples of structural characters that are useful for species identification. Comparison of vertex punctation (Figs. 1 and 2). Comparison of the color of hairs on hind basitarsus (Figs. 3 and 4). Comparison of pubescence on T3–T5 (Figs. 5 and 6). Comparison of labrum shape (Figs. 7 and 8). Comparison of upper interocular distance (Figs. 9 and 10)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887578/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); black hairs predominantly on disc of terga.......................... 8
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
6(5). Upper gena and vertex with fine and scattered punctures, with large impunctate areas (3–5x puncture width); strong metallic blue and green highlights on all tagmata, greener on mesoscutellum and metasoma; discs of metasomal terga with simple yellow hairs (
<figureCitation box="[328,443,932,955]" captionStart="FIGURES 51–54" captionStartId="26.[151,264,1493,1518]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,188,1456]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1435,181,1467]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 51–54. Female of Xylocopa (Schonnherria) ornata Smith, 1874. Fig. 51. Frontal view. Fig. 52. Detail of metasomal terga. Fig. 53. Dorsal habitus. Fig. 54. Lateral habitus. Scale bar 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887602/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Figs. 51–54</figureCitation>
).......................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith, 1874" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1874" box="[1146,1436,932,954]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornata">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1146,1436,932,954]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1146,1309,932,954]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">Xylocopa ornata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, F." box="[1315,1436,932,954]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336" pagination="247 - 302" refId="ref34236" refString="Smith, F. (1874) Monograph of the genus Xylocopa Latr. Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London, 22, 247 - 302. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1874. tb 00168. x" type="journal article" year="1874">Smith, 1874</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead pageId="35" pageNumber="336">- Upper gena and vertex with coarse and dense punctures (1–2x puncture width); distinctive bluish and greenish highlights on all tagmata; whitish, tomentose, plumose hairs on laterodistal margins of T2–T5...................................... 7</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,225,1512]" box="[151,1436,1020,1043]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1020,1043]" pageId="35" pageNumber="336">
7(6). Mesosoma, legs and metasomal terga with mostly yellowish or pale hairs (
